{"id":"1302.0759","submitter":"Eduardo D. Sontag","authors":"Eduardo D. Sontag","title":"A remark about polynomials with specified local minima and no other\n  critical points","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.DS","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The following observation must surely be \"well-known\", but it seems worth\ngiving a simple and quite explicit proof. Take any finite subset X of Rn, n>1.\nThen, there is a polynomial function P:Rn -> R which has local minima on the\nset X, and has no other critical points. Applied to the negative gradient flow\nof P, this implies that there is a polynomial vector field with asymptotically\nstable equilibria on X and no other equilibria. Some trajectories of this\nvector field are not pre-compact; a complementary observation says that, again\nfor arbitrary X, one can find a vector field with asymptotically stable\nequilibria on X, no other equilibria except saddles, and all omega-limit sets\nconsisting of singletons.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 4 Feb 2013 17:13:45 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-02-05"}
